# üß† **1. What Is a Computer Network?**

A **computer network** is a collection of **two or more connected devices** that exchange data and share resources (like files, printers, or internet).

Examples:

* Your phone connected to Wi-Fi ‚Üí local network.
* The Internet ‚Üí the largest global network.

---

# ‚öôÔ∏è **2. Types of Networks (by Size/Scope)**

| Type    | Full Form                 | Coverage Area               | Example             |
| ------- | ------------------------- | --------------------------- | ------------------- |
| **PAN** | Personal Area Network     | Few meters                  | Bluetooth, Hotspot  |
| **LAN** | Local Area Network        | Small building              | College lab, office |
| **MAN** | Metropolitan Area Network | City-wide                   | Cable TV network    |
| **WAN** | Wide Area Network         | Country/Global              | Internet            |
| **VPN** | Virtual Private Network   | Secure tunnel over Internet | Corporate VPN       |

---

# üì∂ **3. Network Topologies**

Topology = **Physical or logical layout** of network connections.

| Topology   | Structure                          | Pros           | Cons                             |
| ---------- | ---------------------------------- | -------------- | -------------------------------- |
| **Bus**    | All devices share one cable        | Simple         | Cable fault ‚Üí all fail           |
| **Star**   | All connect to central hub/switch  | Easy to manage | Hub failure ‚Üí all fail           |
| **Ring**   | Circular connection                | Predictable    | Failure in one link breaks chain |
| **Mesh**   | Every node connects to every other | Very reliable  | Expensive, complex               |
| **Tree**   | Hierarchical                       | Scalable       | Backbone failure affects all     |
| **Hybrid** | Mix of topologies                  | Flexible       | Costly                           |

---

# üì° **4. Network Models**

### a) **OSI Model (7 Layers)**

A theoretical model for understanding communication.

| Layer            | Function                     | Example Protocols |
| ---------------- | ---------------------------- | ----------------- |
| 7Ô∏è‚É£ Application  | User interface, services     | HTTP, FTP, DNS    |
| 6Ô∏è‚É£ Presentation | Encryption, compression      | SSL, JPEG, MPEG   |
| 5Ô∏è‚É£ Session      | Manages sessions             | NetBIOS, RPC      |
| 4Ô∏è‚É£ Transport    | Reliable delivery            | TCP, UDP          |
| 3Ô∏è‚É£ Network      | Logical addressing & routing | IP, ICMP          |
| 2Ô∏è‚É£ Data Link    | Framing, MAC addressing      | Ethernet, PPP     |
| 1Ô∏è‚É£ Physical     | Media, signals               | Cables, radio     |

> üìò **Mnemonic:** *All People Seem To Need Data Processing*

---

### b) **TCP/IP Model (4 Layers)**

Practical version used on the Internet.

| TCP/IP Layer   | Corresponding OSI Layers | Example Protocols |
| -------------- | ------------------------ | ----------------- |
| Application    | 7,6,5                    | HTTP, SMTP, DNS   |
| Transport      | 4                        | TCP, UDP          |
| Internet       | 3                        | IP, ICMP          |
| Network Access | 2,1                      | Ethernet, Wi-Fi   |

---

# üîÅ **5. IP Addressing (IPv4 & IPv6)**

## **IPv4 (32-bit)**

* Format: `192.168.1.10`
* Divided into **Network + Host** parts.
* Represented in **dot-decimal** form.
* Total addresses: `2¬≥¬≤ ‚âà 4.3 billion`

### IPv4 Classes:

| Class | Range                       | Default Mask  | Use             |
| ----- | --------------------------- | ------------- | --------------- |
| A     | 1.0.0.0 ‚Äì 126.255.255.255   | 255.0.0.0     | Big networks    |
| B     | 128.0.0.0 ‚Äì 191.255.255.255 | 255.255.0.0   | Medium networks |
| C     | 192.0.0.0 ‚Äì 223.255.255.255 | 255.255.255.0 | Small networks  |
| D     | 224.0.0.0 ‚Äì 239.255.255.255 | N/A           | Multicast       |
| E     | 240.0.0.0 ‚Äì 255.255.255.255 | N/A           | Experimental    |

---

## **IPv6 (128-bit)**

* Example:
  `2001:0db8:85a3:0000:0000:8a2e:0370:7334`
* Uses **hexadecimal** and **colon-separated** notation.
* Much larger address space (`2¬π¬≤‚Å∏` addresses).
* No need for NAT.
* Supports **auto-configuration, security (IPSec)**, and **multicasting** natively.

---

# üß© **6. Subnetting (IPv4)**

Subnetting = Dividing a network into smaller parts (subnets) for better efficiency & security.

### Example:

Given: `192.168.10.0/26`

* `/26` means 26 bits for network, 6 for host.
* Subnet mask: `255.255.255.192`
* Each subnet has: `2‚Å∂ = 64 addresses`
* Usable per subnet: `64 - 2 = 62` (network + broadcast excluded)
* Subnets:

  * `192.168.10.0 ‚Äì 192.168.10.63`
  * `192.168.10.64 ‚Äì 192.168.10.127`
  * etc.

---

# üöÄ **7. Transport Layer: TCP vs UDP**

| Feature           | **TCP (Transmission Control Protocol)** | **UDP (User Datagram Protocol)** |
| ----------------- | --------------------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| Connection        | Connection-oriented                     | Connectionless                   |
| Reliability       | Reliable (ACK, retransmission)          | Unreliable (no ACK)              |
| Order             | Ordered delivery                        | No guarantee                     |
| Speed             | Slower                                  | Faster                           |
| Use cases         | Web, email, file transfer               | Video streaming, gaming, VoIP    |
| Example Protocols | HTTP, FTP, SMTP                         | DNS, TFTP, DHCP                  |

---

# üîÑ **8. How TCP Works (3-Way Handshake)**

1Ô∏è‚É£ **SYN** ‚Üí Client requests connection
2Ô∏è‚É£ **SYN-ACK** ‚Üí Server acknowledges
3Ô∏è‚É£ **ACK** ‚Üí Client confirms

‚úÖ Now the connection is **established**.

When closing:

* **FIN ‚Üí ACK ‚Üí FIN ‚Üí ACK** ‚Üí graceful termination.

---

# üåç **9. Network Layer (Routing + IP)**

### Functions:

* Logical addressing (assign IPs)
* Routing packets (find best path)
* Fragmentation & Reassembly

### Devices:

* **Router** works at Network Layer.

### Common Protocols:

* IP (Internet Protocol)
* ICMP (for errors & ping)
* ARP (IPv4 to MAC)
* RARP (MAC to IP)

---

# ‚ö° **10. Data Link Layer**

### Functions:

* Framing
* Physical addressing (MAC)
* Error detection/correction

### Devices:

* **Switch, Bridge**

### Example:

Ethernet frame includes:

```
[Dest MAC][Source MAC][Type][Data][CRC]
```

---

# üîå **11. Physical Layer**

* Transmits raw bits over medium.
* Deals with cables, connectors, voltages, etc.
* Examples: Ethernet cable (RJ45), fiber optics, Wi-Fi radio.

---

# üîê **12. Network Devices Summary**

| Device   | OSI Layer | Function                     |
| -------- | --------- | ---------------------------- |
| Hub      | 1         | Broadcasts data to all       |
| Switch   | 2         | Forwards frames based on MAC |
| Router   | 3         | Routes packets using IP      |
| Gateway  | 4‚Äì7       | Converts protocols           |
| Repeater | 1         | Amplifies signal             |
| Bridge   | 2         | Connects LAN segments        |
| Modem    | 1         | Converts digital ‚Üî analog    |

---

# üåê **13. Important Network Concepts**

| Concept       | Meaning                                                                  |
| ------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| **NAT**       | Network Address Translation ‚Äì allows private IPs to use public internet. |
| **DNS**       | Converts domain names to IP addresses.                                   |
| **DHCP**      | Automatically assigns IP addresses.                                      |
| **ARP**       | Maps IP ‚Üí MAC.                                                           |
| **ICMP**      | Error messages and diagnostics (used in ping).                           |
| **Firewalls** | Filter and secure traffic.                                               |
| **VPNs**      | Encrypt connections over Internet.                                       |

---

# üîç **14. Common Network Commands**

| Command                 | Use                             |
| ----------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| `ping`                  | Check connectivity              |
| `ipconfig` / `ifconfig` | Show network configuration      |
| `traceroute`            | Track route packets take        |
| `netstat`               | Show open ports and connections |
| `nslookup`              | DNS query                       |
| `arp -a`                | View ARP table                  |

---

# üìà **15. Network Performance Parameters**

| Metric          | Description                     |
| --------------- | ------------------------------- |
| **Bandwidth**   | Max data transfer rate          |
| **Throughput**  | Actual achieved rate            |
| **Latency**     | Delay between sender & receiver |
| **Jitter**      | Variation in latency            |
| **Packet loss** | % of lost packets               |

---

# üß≠ **16. Summary Diagram (Textual)**

```
USER ‚Üí Application (HTTP)
 ‚Üí Transport (TCP/UDP)
 ‚Üí Network (IP)
 ‚Üí Data Link (Ethernet)
 ‚Üí Physical (Cable/Wi-Fi)
```

Each layer adds its own **header** (encapsulation).
Receiver removes them in reverse (decapsulation).

